1. Potential is stored difference

Potential energy exists whenever a system is not in its lowest-energy configuration.

Examples:
	•	water behind a dam
	•	a stretched spring
	•	a lifted rock
	•	electrical charge separation
	•	chemical bonds

Nothing is moving yet, but the system contains asymmetry.

That asymmetry means motion is possible.

So potential energy is essentially:

stored gradient


⸻

2. Potential shapes the future

Even though potential energy isn’t moving, it determines how motion will occur once movement starts.

Example:

A marble sitting in a bowl.

The marble isn’t moving, but the shape of the bowl defines all possible paths it could take.

Physicists call this the potential landscape.

Motion follows the slope of that landscape.

⸻

3. Potential is geometry

In many areas of physics, potential energy is basically a map of constraints.

Examples:
	•	gravitational potential → shape of spacetime curvature
	•	electric potential → electric field structure
	•	chemical potential → reaction likelihood

So potential is really a field describing what movements are favored.

That’s why it affects kinetic behavior.

